ðŸ‘ðŸ‘GitHub ActionsðŸ‘ðŸ‘ is one of the most powerful CI/CD (Continuous Integration / Continuous Deployment) 
tools built directly into GitHub. Letâ€™s break it down clearly:

ðŸ§© What is GitHub Actions?
GitHub Actions helps you automate tasks in your software development lifecycle â€” like:
Building your code automatically when you push commits.
Running tests.
Building Docker images.
Deploying applications to environments like GCP, AWS, Azure, or Kubernetes.
Sending notifications or triggering custom workflows.

It works by defining workflows using YAML files inside your repository.
âš™ï¸ Where it lives
You store your workflows under:
.github/workflows/
Each YAML file in that folder defines a pipeline (workflow).
Example:
.github/
 â””â”€â”€ workflows/
      â””â”€â”€ ci.yml

ðŸš€ How it works (in short)
A GitHub Actions workflow runs in response to events, such as:
push
pull_request
schedule
workflow_dispatch (manual trigger)
Each workflow has:
Jobs (that can run in parallel or sequence)
Steps (individual commands or reusable actions)
Runners (machines that execute your jobs â€” GitHub provides Linux, Windows, macOS runners)
ðŸ§  Basic Example â€” Node.js app CI

Hereâ€™s a simple example of a workflow that runs tests whenever you push code.
# .github/workflows/node-ci.yml
name: Node.js CI
on:
  push:
    branches: [ "main" ]
  pull_request:
    branches: [ "main" ]

jobs:
  build:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
      - name: Checkout repository
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Setup Node.js
        uses: actions/setup-node@v4
        with:
          node-version: '20'

      - name: Install dependencies
        run: npm install

      - name: Run tests
        run: npm test

ðŸ”§ How to Create and Use It

Go to your GitHub repo â†’ click on â€œActionsâ€ tab.
Click â€œNew workflowâ€ â†’ you can pick a template or set up your own.
Create a YAML file (like the one above) under .github/workflows/.

Commit and push the file.
GitHub automatically runs the workflow on the next event (like push or pull_request).
ðŸŒ Example â€” Deploy to GKE (Google Kubernetes Engine)

Hereâ€™s a simple example that builds a Docker image and deploys it to GKE:

name: Deploy to GKE

on:
  push:
    branches: [ "main" ]

jobs:
  deploy:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
      - name: Checkout code
        uses: actions/checkout@v4

      - name: Set up Google Cloud SDK
        uses: google-github-actions/setup-gcloud@v2
        with:
          project_id: ${{ secrets.GCP_PROJECT_ID }}
          service_account_key: ${{ secrets.GCP_SA_KEY }}

      - name: Configure Docker
        run: gcloud auth configure-docker

      - name: Build and push Docker image
        run: |
          docker build -t gcr.io/${{ secrets.GCP_PROJECT_ID }}/myapp:${{ github.sha }} .
          docker push gcr.io/${{ secrets.GCP_PROJECT_ID }}/myapp:${{ github.sha }}

      - name: Deploy to GKE
        run: |
          gcloud container clusters get-credentials my-cluster --region europe-west2
          kubectl set image deployment/myapp myapp=gcr.io/${{ secrets.GCP_PROJECT_ID }}/myapp:${{ github.sha }}

ðŸ”’ Secrets Management
You can store secrets (like credentials, tokens, etc.) safely in:
Repo â†’ Settings â†’ Secrets and variables â†’ Actions
Use them inside workflows like:
${{ secrets.MY_SECRET_NAME }}

